Huawei has launched its new P30 and P30 Pro smartphones, which are set to take on the Samsung Galaxy S10 and S10+ in South Africa. The new devices include a number of flagship features, such as in-screen fingerprint sensors and OLED displays. The P30 and P30 Pro offer great new camera functionality in addition to an overhauled design which minimises the presence of the front camera notch while expanding the edges of the OLED display. The P30 Pro also sports a dedicated TOF lens for improved bokeh effects and object detection, along with support for standard and reverse wireless charging. Additionally, support for for dual-SIM configurations with NanoSD storage compatibility has been included. Huawei’s new smartphones will compete against Samsung’s high-end devices locally, as both Samsung and Huawei’s devices boast impressive displays, specifications, and designs. Both devices also run Android, with the Huawei devices running EMUI 9.1: Huawei’s adapted version of Android 9.0. An area where Huawei’s new flagships could prove more attractive, however, is price. While Huawei has not yet listed official pricing for its devices, South African retailers have published the following initial pre-order prices: In comparison, Samsung’s Galaxy S10 range is priced as follows: A comparison of the specifications and base prices for the Huawei P30 and Galaxy S10 line-ups is below. <img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-300638" src="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Samsung-Galaxy-S10-vs-Huawei-P30.jpg" alt="Samsung Galaxy S10 vs Huawei P30" width="640" height="430" srcset="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Samsung-Galaxy-S10-vs-Huawei-P30.jpg 640w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Samsung-Galaxy-S10-vs-Huawei-P30-300x202.jpg 300w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Samsung-Galaxy-S10-vs-Huawei-P30-595x400.jpg 595w" sizes="(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: